snippet.textDisplay:
Clearly, Binienda and his people committed the popular fault of underestimating Tommy Fury. He was not ready for an instant assault from a boxer with world-class skills, and Tommy barely wasted a step, a breath or a punch. There was no end in sight for Binienda other than a severe beating and a full KO, and the referee acted perfectly.


If Tommy was a couple of inches taller he would be able to carry enough weight to become a successful heavyweight. If, at the same height as Mike Tyson he could carry the same muscle-mass as the great man, he could have an outside chance of making World Champion as a heavyweight. As it is other lightweights are certainly now paying more attention to Tommy Fury than did Binienda and company.


I would really like to see Tommy Fury working with a top American trainer, just to enable him to get full recognition for his skills, mind-set and physique and not reduced to being no more than "Tyson Fury's half-brother" and "one heck of a guy with the ladies"... No jealousy on that last point from me, btw, since 50 years ago I was a boxer for my university, with far more success out of the ring than in it. I was also a rubbish student!
